 1	# Deepkit Restate
 2	
 3	**Deepkit Restate** is a seamless [Restate](https://restate.dev) integration for [Deepkit](https://deepkit.io). It enables effortless communication between distributed services using durable invocations, service interfaces, and event-driven architecture.
 4	
 5	> This documentation assumes familiarity with Deepkit **and** Restate's concepts and lifecycle.
 6	
 7	---
 8	
 9	## Installation
 10	
 11	```bash
 12	npm add deepkit-restate
 13	```
 14	
 15	---
 16	
 17	## Module Setup
 18	
 19	To use Deepkit Restate, import the `RestateModule` and provide configuration for the components you need:
 20	
 21	```ts
 22	import { FrameworkModule } from '@deepkit/framework';
 23	import { RestateModule } from 'deepkit-restate';
 24	import { App } from '@deepkit/app';
 25	
 26	const app = new App({
 27	 imports: [
 28	 new FrameworkModule(),
 29	 new RestateModule({
 30	 server: {
 31	 host: 'http://localhost',
 32	 port: 9080,
 33	 },
 34	 ingress: {
 35	 url: 'http://localhost:8080',
 36	 },
 37	 pubsub: {
 38	 cluster: 'default',
 39	 defaultStream: 'all',
 40	 sse: {
 41	 url: 'http://localhost:3000',
 42	 },
 43	 },
 44	 admin: {
 45	 url: 'http://0.0.0.0:9070',
 46	 deployOnStartup: true,
 47	 },
 48	 }),
 49	 ],
 50	});
 51	```
 52	
 53	You can configure any combination of the following:
 54	
 55	- **server**: Starts a Restate server
 56	- **ingress**: Enables outbound service calls
 57	- **pubsub**: Enables pub/sub event system
 58	- **admin**: Registers deployments with the admin interface
 59	
 60	> If a section is not configured, that functionality will not be available.
 61	
 62	---
 63	
 64	## Serialization (Serde) and Error Handling
 65	
 66	All serialization and deserialization in Deepkit Restate is handled via **BSON** by default.
 67	
 68	This means you can **return** and **accept** any types in your service handlers or saga steps, including:
 69	
 70	- Primitives (`string`, `number`, `boolean`, etc.)
 71	- Plain objects (`{ name: string; age: number }`)
 72	- Class instances (with properties and methods)
 73	- Complex nested types and arrays
 74	- Custom types supported by BSON serialization
 75	
 76	The serialization system preserves type fidelity and structure when encoding and decoding data across the network.
 77	
 78	### Automatic Error Forwarding and Serialization
 79	
 80	- If an error is **thrown** inside a handler or saga step, it is automatically serialized and forwarded to the caller.
 81	- This allows errors to be **caught** remotely, preserving the error information.
 82	- **Custom errors with type information** are supported and **will not be retried** automatically by the system, enabling precise control over error handling and retries.
 83	
 84	> We are actively working on an adapter to support JSON serialization as an alternative to BSON.
 85	
 86	---
 87	
 88	## Calling Services
 89	
 90	### `RestateClient`
 91	
 92	The `RestateClient` handles communication between services and objects. It behaves differently depending on whether it is used within or outside an invocation context.
 93	
 94	You can create an ingress client manually:
 95	
 96	```ts
 97	import { RestateIngressClient } from 'deepkit-restate';
 98	
 99	const client = new RestateIngressClient({ url: 'http://localhost:9080' });
 100	```
 101	
 102	Or retrieve the configured instance via DI:
 103	
 104	```ts
 105	const client = app.get<RestateClient>();
 106	```
 107	
 108	### Using the Client
 109	
 110	To create a proxy to a **service**:
 111	
 112	```ts
 113	const user = client.service<UserServiceApi>();
 114	```
 115	
 116	To create a proxy to an **object**:
 117	
 118	```ts
 119	const user = client.object<UserObjectApi>();
 120	```
 121	
 122	### Invoking Methods
 123	
 124	Durable request (waits for a result):
 125	
 126	```ts
 127	await client.call(user.create());
 128	```
 129	
 130	Fire-and-forget (does not wait for result):
 131	
 132	```ts
 133	await client.send(user.create());
 134	```
 135	
 136	You can configure delivery options:
 137	
 138	```ts
 139	await client.send(user.create(), { delay: '10s' });
 140	```
 141	
 142	For object calls, specify the key:
 143	
 144	```ts
 145	await client.call('user-key', user.create());
 146	await client.send('user-key', user.create());
 147	```
 148	
 149	---
 150	
 151	## Defining Services and Objects
 152	
 153	### Services
 154	
 155	```ts
 156	interface UserServiceHandlers {
 157	 create(username: string): Promise<User>;
 158	}
 159	
 160	type UserServiceApi = RestateService<'user', UserServiceHandlers>;
 161	
 162	@restate.service<UserServiceApi>()
 163	class UserService implements UserServiceHandlers {
 164	 constructor(private readonly ctx: RestateServiceContext) {}
 165	
 166	 @restate.handler()
 167	 async create(username: string): Promise<User> {
 168	 return User.create(this.ctx, username);
 169	 }
 170	}
 171	```
 172	
 173	- Use `@restate.service()` to define a service.
 174	- Use `@restate.handler()` define handlers.
 175	- The context (`RestateServiceContext`) provides durable execution helpers.
 176	
 177	### Objects
 178	
 179	```ts
 180	interface UserObjectHandlers {}
 181	
 182	type UserObjectApi = RestateObject<'user', UserObjectHandlers>;
 183	
 184	@restate.object<UserObjectApi>()
 185	class UserObject implements UserObjectHandlers {}
 186	```
 187	
 188	Use `@restate.object()` to define virtual objects.
 189	
 190	> Shared handlers can be declared using `@restate.shared().handler()`.
 191	> **Note:** Shared handlers use the object context, which is not type-safe. Avoid using `ctx.set()` at runtime in shared handlers.
 192	
 193	---
 194	
 195	## Dependency Injection: Calling Other Services
 196	
 197	You can inject the client and proxy APIs into a service:
 198	
 199	```ts
 200	@restate.service<UserServiceApi>()
 201	class UserService {
 202	 constructor(
 203	 private readonly client: RestateClient,
 204	 private readonly payment: PaymentServiceApi,
 205	 ) {}
 206	
 207	 @restate.handler()
 208	 async create(user: User): Promise<void> {
 209	 await this.client.call(this.payment.create('Test', user));
 210	 }
 211	}
 212	```
 213	
 214	For objects, remember to provide a key:
 215	
 216	```ts
 217	await this.client.call('payment-id', this.payment.create('Test'));
 218	```
 219	
 220	---
 221	
 222	## Durable Helpers
 223	
 224	### `run` blocks
 225	
 226	The `ctx.run()` helper ensures a block is executed durably:
 227	
 228	```ts
 229	const user = await this.ctx.run<User>('create user', () => new User(username));
 230	```
 231	
 232	Without a type argument, the return value is ignored:
 233	
 234	```ts
 235	const none = await this.ctx.run('create user', () => new User(username));
 236	```
 237	
 238	### Awakeables
 239	
 240	Used to pause and resume execution:
 241	
 242	```ts
 243	const awakeable = this.ctx.awakeable<User>();
 244	```
 245	
 246	To resume:
 247	
 248	```ts
 249	this.ctx.resolveAwakeable<User>();
 250	```
 251	
 252	### Durable State
 253	
 254	Store and retrieve durable state using the context:
 255	
 256	```ts
 257	await this.ctx.set<User>('user', user);
 258	```
 259	
 260	```ts
 261	const user = await this.ctx.get<User>('user');
 262	```
 263	
 264	---
 265	
 266	## Pub/Sub
 267	
 268	### Server Setup
 269	
 270	Set up a dedicated application for handling events.
 271	
 272	```ts
 273	import { App } from '@deepkit/app';
 274	import { FrameworkModule } from '@deepkit/framework';
 275	import { RestateModule } from 'deepkit-restate';
 276	import { RestatePubsubServerModule } from 'deepkit-restate/pubsub-server';
 277	
 278	await new App({
 279	 imports: [
 280	 new FrameworkModule({ port: 9090 }),
 281	 new RestateModule({ server: { port: 9080 } }),
 282	 new RestatePubSubServerModule({
 283	 sse: {
 284	 all: true,
 285	 autoDiscover: true,
 286	 nodes: ['localhost:9090'],
 287	 },
 288	 }),
 289	 ],
 290	}).run();
 291	```
 292	
 293	### Publishing Events
 294	
 295	Inside a service handler (durable):
 296	
 297	```ts
 298	constructor(private readonly publisher: RestateEventPublisher) {}
 299	
 300	await this.publisher.publish([new UserCreatedEvent(user)]);
 301	```
 302	
 303	Outside of invocation (non-durable):
 304	
 305	```ts
 306	const publisher = app.get<RestateEventPublisher>();
 307	await publisher.publish([new UserCreatedEvent(user)]);
 308	```
 309	
 310	> Only classes are supported as events.
 311	
 312	> Events are versioned by hashing their structure.
 313	
 314	### Handling Events
 315	
 316	Only services can define event handlers:
 317	
 318	```ts
 319	@restate.service<UserServiceApi>()
 320	class UserService {
 321	 @(restate.event<UserCreatedEvent>().handler())
 322	 async onUserCreated(event: UserCreatedEvent): Promise<void> {
 323	 // handle event
 324	 }
 325	}
 326	```
 327	
 328	### SSE Delivery
 329	
 330	Server-Sent Events (SSE) allow real-time delivery of events to connected subscribers.
 331	
 332	#### Subscribing to Events Outside of Services
 333	
 334	Subscribe to events from contexts like HTTP or RPC controllers:
 335	
 336	```ts
 337	const subscriber = app.get<RestateEventSubscriber>();
 338	
 339	const unsubscribe = await subscriber.subscribe<UserCreatedEvent>(event => {
 340	 // handle event
 341	});
 342	
 343	await unsubscribe();
 344	```
 345	
 346	You can also use union types to subscribe to multiple events.
 347	
 348	#### Configuration (Global)
 349	
 350	You can configure global SSE delivery behavior in `RestatePubSubServerModule`:
 351	
 352	```ts
 353	new RestatePubSubServerModule({
 354	 sse: {
 355	 all: true,
 356	 autoDiscover: true,
 357	 nodes: ['events-1.internal:9090', 'events-2.internal:9090'],
 358	 },
 359	});
 360	```
 361	
 362	| Option | Type | Description |
 363	|--------------------| ---------- |-------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
 364	| `sse.all` | `boolean` | If `true`, all published events will be delivered via SSE by default. |
 365	| `sse.autoDiscover` | `boolean` | When enabled, resolves peer IPs via DNS to fan out SSE events to other nodes. |
 366	| `sse.nodes` | `string[]` | List of peer server URLs for fan-out. |
 367	
 368	> SSE fan-out is stateless and opportunistic. Each node will attempt to push matching events to other known nodes.
 369	
 370	#### Overriding per Publish
 371	
 372	You can override the global SSE setting by passing `{ sse: true }` in the publish options:
 373	
 374	```ts
 375	await publisher.publish([new UserCreatedEvent(user)], {
 376	 sse: true,
 377	});
 378	```
 379	
 380	Behavior summary:
 381	
 382	- If `sse.all` is **true**, SSE is used by default unless explicitly disabled.
 383	- If `sse.all` is **false**, SSE is off by default but you can still enable it by passing `sse: true`.
 384	
 385	> Only events published with SSE enabled will be streamed to subscribers.
 386	
 387	# Sagas
 388	
 389	Sagas provide a powerful way to orchestrate complex, long-running workflows that involve multiple services. They support **stepwise execution**, **compensation (rollback)**, **reply handling**, and **waiting for external events** (via awakeables).
 390	
 391	---
 392	
 393	## What is a Saga?
 394	
 395	A **Saga** is a workflow pattern that manages distributed transactions and side effects in a coordinated way, including compensations for failures. In Deepkit Restate, you define sagas by extending the `Saga<T>` class and using the `@restate.saga<Api>()` decorator.
 396	
 397	---
 398	
 399	## Defining a Saga Workflow
 400	
 401	Sagas are defined using a fluent builder pattern in the `definition` property:
 402	
 403	- `step()`: Defines a new step in the saga.
 404	- `invoke(handler)`: Calls a method in your saga class to perform an action or service call.
 405	- `compensate(handler)`: Defines a rollback method if the step fails or the saga is aborted.
 406	- `onReply<EventType>(handler)`: Registers an event handler for replies to invoked actions.
 407	- `build()`: Finalizes the saga definition.
 408	
 409	---
 410	
 411	## Awakeables
 412	
 413	Awakeables are special constructs to **wait for asynchronous external events**. They provide a promise you can `await` to pause saga execution until an event occurs.
 414	
 415	Create awakeables with the saga context inside your saga methods:
 416	
 417	```ts
 418	this.confirmTicketAwakeable = this.ctx.awakeable<TicketConfirmed>();
 419	```
 420	
 421	---
 422	
 423	## Using the Saga Context
 424	
 425	The `RestateSagaContext` (`this.ctx`) provides utilities like:
 426	
 427	- `awakeable<T>()`: Creates an awakeable to wait for events.
 428	- `set<T>(key, value)`: Persist state data during saga execution.
 429	- `get<T>(key)`: Retrieve persisted state.
 430	
 431	---
 432	
 433	## Calling Other Services
 434	
 435	All service calls inside invocation handlers automatically use the underlying `client.call`. This means:
 436	
 437	- You **do not need to manually call `client.call`** within your saga handlers.
 438	- Only **service calls** are supported currently (no direct calls to objects).
 439	- The framework handles communication and reply handling.
 440	
 441	---
 442	
 443	## Example: Simplified CreateOrderSaga
 444	
 445	```ts
 446	import {
 447	 restate,
 448	 Saga,
 449	 RestateSagaContext,
 450	 RestateAwakeable,
 451	} from 'deepkit-restate';
 452	
 453	@restate.saga<CreateOrderSagaApi>()
 454	export class CreateOrderSaga extends Saga<CreateOrderSagaData> {
 455	 confirmTicketAwakeable?: RestateAwakeable<TicketConfirmed>;
 456	
 457	 readonly definition = this.step()
 458	 .invoke(this.create)
 459	 .compensate(this.reject)
 460	 .step()
 461	 .invoke(this.createTicket)
 462	 .onReply<TicketCreated>(this.handleTicketCreated)
 463	 .step()
 464	 .invoke(this.waitForTicketConfirmation)
 465	 .build();
 466	
 467	 constructor(
 468	 private readonly order: OrderServiceApi,
 469	 private readonly kitchen: KitchenServiceApi,
 470	 private readonly ctx: RestateSagaContext,
 471	 ) {
 472	 super();
 473	 }
 474	
 475	 create(data: CreateOrderSagaData) {
 476	 return this.order.create(data.orderId, data.orderDetails);
 477	 }
 478	
 479	 reject(data: CreateOrderSagaData) {
 480	 return this.order.reject(data.orderId);
 481	 }
 482	
 483	 createTicket(data: CreateOrderSagaData) {
 484	 this.confirmTicketAwakeable = this.ctx.awakeable<TicketConfirmed>();
 485	 return this.kitchen.createTicket(
 486	 data.orderDetails.restaurantId,
 487	 data.orderId,
 488	 data.orderDetails.lineItems,
 489	 this.confirmTicketAwakeable.id,
 490	 );
 491	 }
 492	
 493	 handleTicketCreated(data: CreateOrderSagaData, event: TicketCreated) {
 494	 data.ticketId = event.ticketId;
 495	 }
 496	
 497	 async waitForTicketConfirmation(data: CreateOrderSagaData) {
 498	 await this.confirmTicketAwakeable!.promise;
 499	 }
 500	}
 501	```
 502	
 503	## Starting a Saga and Retrieving Its State
 504	
 505	After defining your saga, you typically want to **start** an instance of it and later **query its state** to track progress or outcome.
 506	
 507	### Creating a Saga Client
 508	
 509	Use the client to create a saga proxy:
 510	
 511	```ts
 512	const createOrderSaga = client.saga<CreateOrderSagaApi>();
 513	```
 514	
 515	This creates a handle to interact with the saga.
 516	
 517	---
 518	
 519	### Starting a Saga Instance
 520	
 521	To start a saga, call `start` with the sagas unique ID and initial input data:
 522	
 523	```ts
 524	const startStatus = await createOrderSaga.start(orderId, {
 525	 id: orderId,
 526	 orderTotal: 10.5,
 527	 customerId,
 528	});
 529	```
 530	
 531	- `orderId` uniquely identifies the saga instance.
 532	- The second argument is the initial data payload to pass to the saga.
 533	- `start` returns the initial status of saga execution.
 534	
 535	---
 536	
 537	### Querying the Saga State
 538	
 539	At any time, you can query the current state of the saga instance by its ID using `state`:
 540	
 541	```ts
 542	const state = await createOrderSaga.state(orderId);
 543	```
 544	
 545	This returns the persisted saga data reflecting its current progress, e.g., which step it is on, and any state variables updated along the way.
 546	
 547	---
 548	
 549	### Notes
 550	
 551	- The saga `start` call triggers the first step of your saga workflow.
 552	- The saga state reflects all persisted data and progress, useful for monitoring or troubleshooting.
 553	- You can invoke `start` only once per unique saga instance ID.
 554	- Subsequent state changes happen asynchronously as the saga progresses.
 555	
 556	### Summary
 557	
 558	- Sagas manage multi-step distributed workflows with clear compensation.
 559	- Steps can invoke service calls, wait for replies, or wait for external events.
 560	- Awakeables let you asynchronously wait inside sagas for external confirmations.
 561	- Saga state can be persisted and retrieved with the saga context.
 562	- Invocation handlers automatically handle calling services; no manual client calls needed.
 563	- Currently, only service calls are supported, no direct object calls with keys.
 564	- Compensation methods help rollback on failure or abort scenarios.
